INSERT INTO public.documents (id, slug, title, content, status, document_type, source_type, source_id, source_url, tags, metadata, last_synced_at, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (5, 'campaign_builder', 'Launch10 - Google Ad Campaign Builder - AI FAQ/Support', 'Create - Content
Ad Group Name
Question: What is an “Ad Group”?
Answer: An Ad Group is a container inside your Google Ads campaign that holds:
A set of ads (your headlines and details)
A set of related keywords or search themes
The Ad Group Name is for your internal organization. Customers never see it, but it matters because:
It helps you keep campaigns organized as you add more ads in the future.
It gives Launch10 and Google context about the theme of your ad, which can improve suggestions and relevance.
It often becomes the label you use later when looking at performance reports.
Good Ad Group Names are short and specific, for example:
“Dog Walking – Brooklyn Heights”
“Emergency Plumbing – After Hours”
“Online Guitar Lessons – Beginner”


Question: Is there a character limit for the Ad Group Name?
Answer: We follow Google’s limits behind the scenes. Practically speaking:
Keep Ad Group Names short and scannable, ideally under 80 characters.
Use plain text without emojis or special characters, which can make reporting harder to read.
If you hit a limit, you will see a validation error and can shorten the name.

Headlines
Question: What are Headlines in my ad?
Answer: Headlines are short text snippets (up to 30 characters each) that appear as the bold, clickable part of your Google Search ad.
In a live ad, Google usually shows 2–3 headlines at a time, side by side. With Responsive Search Ads, Google can test different combinations of the headlines you provide.
On this page, you can:
Enter your own headlines
Edit AI-generated suggestions
Add extra headline options for Google to test
Question: Why do I see “Select 3–15” for Headlines?
Answer: Google requires that a Responsive Search Ad has:
At least 3 active headlines
Up to 15 total headlines
Launch10 lets you:
Add many headline ideas.
Choose which ones count as active (up to 15). Make sure to click the lock for headlines you’d like to keep
Your campaign cannot be launched until at least 3 headlines are selected.

Question: How many headlines should I actually use?
Answer: We recommend:
Minimum: 3 (required by Google)
Better: 5–8
Maximum: 15
More high-quality options give Google more combinations to test, which can improve performance over time. However, avoid filling all 15 with only tiny variations. Aim for meaningful differences in message or angle.

Question: How does Launch10’s AI use my answers from earlier steps to suggest headlines?
Answer: We use everything you shared during the Brainstorm and Landing Page steps, including:
Your business type and services
Your ideal customer
Your tone and style preferences
Any offers, pricing, or location details
Launch10 uses this context to generate headlines that:
Match your landing page content
Include relevant search phrases
Stay consistent with your page, so the ad and page feel like one seamless experience
You can fully edit these suggestions. Once you change and lock a headline, we treat your version as the source of truth.

Question: What does “Refresh Suggestions” do for Headlines?
Answer: “Refresh Suggestions” will:
Ask the AI to generate a new set of headline ideas, based on your latest business info and page content.
Leave any existing headlines you have edited and locked in place.
Add the new suggestions below headlines that are already locked 
If you manually wrote or edited a headline and then locked it, that content will not be overwritten without your action.

Question: Will Launch10 check if my headlines comply with Google Ads policies?
Answer: We do our best to keep suggestions within common Google Ads guidelines, but:
Google makes the final decision about ad approval.
If Google flags or disapproves a headline, you may need to adjust wording (for example, remove prohibited claims, sensitive content, or certain trademarks).
If a headline is rejected, you can:
Edit it manually, or
Use “Refresh Suggestions” and pick an alternative.

Details (Descriptions)
Question: What are “Details”?
Answer: Details on this page represent the description lines of your Responsive Search Ad. Each detail:
Can be up to 90 characters.
Appears below your headlines in search results.
Gives you space to explain benefits, features, and calls to action.
Google usually shows up to 2 description lines in a single ad impression.

Question: How should I write effective Details?
Answer: A good description should:
Expand on the headline
Give more context, benefits, or proof.
Address objections
Mention trust signals (reviews, guarantees, certifications).
Include a clear call to action
“Book now,” “Get a free quote,” “Schedule your session.”
Examples:
“Personalized pet portraits, shot in-home or in studio. Book online in minutes.”
“Licensed plumbers on call 24/7. Upfront pricing and fast emergency service.”
“Try our software free for 14 days. No credit card required.”
Avoid misleading claims or language that could be seen as spammy.

Question: What happens if my Detail text is longer than the limit?
Answer: Each Detail has a character counter. If you exceed the 90-character limit:
The counter will show that you are over the limit.
We prevent you from saving or moving forward until you shorten it.
Shorten by:
Removing filler words.
Focusing on one primary benefit and a call to action.

Question: How does Launch10’s AI create Details? Can I change them?
Answer: We use your earlier answers (business info, customers, offer, tone), your landing page copy, and your selected headlines to generate description options that reinforce your main value proposition, stay within character limits, and use clear calls to action
You can fully edit each Detail. Your edits take priority over AI suggestions and will be used for the final ad.

General Content Page Questions
Question: What if I am not sure what to write?
Answer: You have a few options:
Start with AI suggestions
Click “Refresh Suggestions” for both Headlines and Details.
Then lightly edit for accuracy and voice.
Describe your offer in plain language
Write how you would explain it to a friend.
Keep sentences short and direct.
Use a simple formula
Headline: Service or benefit plus who it is for.
Detail 1: What you do and why it is good.
Detail 2: Social proof or guarantee plus call to action.
You can always revise later after seeing performance.

Question: Will changing my content later affect my campaign?
Answer: Yes. When you edit Headlines or Details after launch:
We will sync the changes to Google Ads.
Google may need some time to re-learn which combinations perform best.
Your previous performance data stays in Google, but the “learning” phase may restart for new content.
Small, focused changes are usually better than rewriting everything at once unless you are repositioning your offer.

Question: What if I see an error message or cannot continue from this page?
Answer: Common reasons you may not be able to proceed:
Fewer than 3 selected headlines.
Fewer than 2 selected details.
A headline over 30 characters or a detail over 90 characters.
Required fields left blank.
Check:
That you have enough selected options in each section.
That character counters are within the limit.
That your Ad Group Name is filled in.
If issues persist, you can:
Remove any recently added content and try again.
Ask the in-product assistant for help by describing what you were trying to do.

Question: How does this Content page relate to the “Highlights” tab?
Answer: On the Content tab you write the main ad text that appears in almost every impression.
On the Highlights tab (next step):
You will usually add structured information such as features, service types, or callouts, depending on the configuration.
These often map to Google ad extensions (now called “assets”), which can show in addition to your headlines and descriptions.
You should complete the Content tab first, since this is the foundation of your ad.
Question: How does the Ad Preview at the top work?
Answer: At the top of the page you’ll see an Ad Preview card:
It updates as you edit your headlines and details.
It shows a sample combination of your content, not every possible version.
Different customers in Google Search may see different headline/description combinations than the one in the preview.

The preview is meant to help you visualize the ad and check for typos, tone, and messaging—not to represent all variations.

Question: Can I bulk add headlines instead of typing them one by one?
Answer: Yes. On the Content page you can paste several headlines at once instead of typing them one by one.
A simple workflow:
Prepare your list
Create your headlines in a text editor or spreadsheet.
Put each headline on its own line and keep them under 30 characters.
Paste into the headline input
Click in the main “Enter headline” field.
Paste your list of headlines.
We will detect line breaks and split them into separate headline rows.
Review and select
Check that each new row looks correct and is within the character limit.
Use “Select 3–15” to choose which ones are active for your ad.
You can still edit or delete any individual headline after a bulk paste, and you can combine bulk-added headlines with AI-generated suggestions.

Create - Highlights
Page Overview
The Highlights tab lets you add extra information that can appear with your Google Search ad, on top of your headlines and descriptions.
On this page you set:
Unique Features Short phrases that highlight special benefits or selling points.
Product or Service Offerings A labeled list of what you offer, grouped under a category like “Services,” “Types,” or “Styles.”
Google treats these as ad assets (previously called extensions). They give your ad more real estate in search results and more reasons for people to click.
Unique Features (Callout Assets)
Question: What are “Unique Features” and where do they appear?
Answer: Unique Features are short phrases that highlight your key benefits. In Google Ads, these map to Callout Assets.
Examples:
“Free consultation”
“Same-day appointments”
“Locally owned and operated”
“Studio or in-home sessions”
When Google decides to show them, they appear as a line of short phrases below your main ad text. They are not clickable on their own, but they:
Make your ad more prominent.
Add extra reasons for customers to choose you.

Question: How are Unique Features different from Headlines and Details?
Answer:
Headlines are the main clickable blue text in your ad.
Details (or descriptions) are longer sentences that explain what you do.
Unique Features are very short, punchy phrases that stack on top of your existing ad text.
Think of Unique Features as quick “bonus reasons” to choose you. They should not repeat entire sentences from your descriptions. Instead, they should call out standout perks.

Question: What does “Select 2–10” mean for Unique Features?
Answer: We allow you to enter many Unique Feature options, but Google requires that only a subset be active at any time.
You must select at least 2 Unique Features on this page.
You can select up to 10 to give Google more options.
Your campaign cannot be launched until you have at least 2 selected Unique Features.

Question: How long can a Unique Feature be?
Answer: We let you write up to a short sentence with a 25 character limit (you will see a character counter next to the input box).
Best practice:
Keep Unique Features brief so they can display cleanly on both desktop and mobile.
Aim for a few words or up to one short line, even if the field technically allows more.

Question: How does Launch10’s AI generate Unique Feature suggestions?
Answer: We use what you told us during Brainstorm (business, offer, audience), your Landing Page content, and your Headlines and Details. Using this context, the AI suggests Unique Features that reflect your real offering, emphasize benefits, trust, or convenience, stay within reasonable length.
You can fully edit or delete any suggestion. Once you edit a feature, that edited version becomes the source of truth.

Question: What does “Refresh Suggestions” do for Unique Features?
Answer: “Refresh Suggestions” will:
Ask Launch10 to generate new Unique Feature ideas based on your latest information.
Leave your existing edited features in place.
Either add new options to the list or replace only unlocked suggestions
Use it when:
You are not happy with the current ideas.
You changed your offer or positioning and want new wording.

Question: What does the “lock” button on a Unique Feature do?
Answer: The lock button lets you protect a specific Unique Feature that you definitely want to use in your campaign.
When you click the lock icon on a line:
That Unique Feature is included in your campaign, as long as it passes Google’s policy checks.
It will not be replaced or removed if you click “Refresh Suggestions”. New suggestions will appear around it, but the locked line stays exactly as you wrote it.
It is also treated as selected/active, so it counts toward your required number of Unique Features.
Use the lock when you have a line that is essential to your message and you do not want AI-generated suggestions to overwrite or swap it out.
Question: What happens if I leave Unique Features blank?
Answer: In many cases your ad can still run with just headlines and descriptions, but:
You will miss an opportunity to take up more space in search results.
Your ad may feel less compelling compared to competitors using callouts.
We encourage you to add at least 2 Unique Features because they are a quick way to improve performance.

Product or Service Offerings (Structured Snippet Assets)
Question: What are “Product or Service Offerings” on this page?
Answer: This section represents Structured Snippet Assets in Google Ads.
They show as:
A category label (such as “Services” or “Styles”)
Followed by a list of values (the items you offer)
Example:
Services: In-Studio Portraits, Outdoor Sessions, Holiday Cards
These snippets:
Help customers quickly see the range of what you offer.
Make your ad look more complete and trustworthy.

Question: What is the “Category” dropdown?
Answer: The Category dropdown controls the label that appears before your list.
Examples of categories:
Services
Types
Styles
Destinations
Brands
Courses
Neighborhoods
You cannot free-type this label. Google provides a predefined list of categories and we map to those options.
Choosing the right category helps Google understand your business and display your snippets appropriately.

Question: How do I choose the right Category?
Answer: Pick the category that best describes how your list items fit together.
For “pet photography” examples:
Services – if your list items are types of services (studio sessions, outdoor sessions).
Types – if your items are portrait types (solo pets, pets with families, holiday sessions).
Styles – if items are artistic styles (classic, lifestyle, candid, black-and-white).
If more than one category seems right, choose the one that would be clearest to a new customer who has never heard of you.

Question: What are the “Details” / values in this section and how many can I add?
Answer: Each value is a single offering that fits under your chosen category.
Examples for a “Services” category:
“In-studio portraits”
“In-home sessions”
“Outdoor park sessions”
“Holiday card shoots”
On this page you will see a control that says “Select 3–10.” That means:
You must select at least 3 values to activate.
You can select up to 10 for a Category.
You can add additional items using Add Value

Question: How does Launch10’s help with Product or Service Offerings?
Answer: We use the information from:
Your Brainstorm answers
Your landing page sections
Your selected headlines and details
to suggest:
A suitable Category
A list of values that match your actual offerings
You can:
Change the Category from the dropdown.
Edit any value.
Add or remove items as needed.
Once edited, your version overrides our suggestion.

General Highlights Questions
Questions: Do Highlights always show with my ad?
Answer: No. Google decides when to show each asset based on:
The customer’s device and context.
The space available on the results page.
The expected impact on performance.
Sometimes customers will see your ad with both Unique Features and Offerings, sometimes with only one type, and sometimes with just the core text. This is normal.

Question: Why can’t I move forward from the Highlights page?
Answer: Common reasons:
You have fewer than 2 selected Unique Features.
You have fewer than 3 selected Offerings in the Product or Service section.
A field is over the character limit or left completely blank.
Check:
That you see “Selected” counts that meet the minimums in both sections.
That each active item has valid text and no error messages.
That your Category is set for Product or Service Offerings.
Once everything is valid and the minimum selections are met, you should be able to continue to the Plan step.

Plan - Keyword Targeting
Keyword Targeting
Question: What are keywords?
Answer: Keywords are the words and short phrases people type into Google when they are searching for something. Your ad becomes eligible to show when someone’s search is related to the keywords in your campaign. Strong, relevant keywords help Google match your ad with the right customers, which leads to higher-quality clicks and better results for your budget.

Question: Will customers see my keywords?
Answer: Customers do not see your exact keyword list. They see your ad text (headlines, details, and highlights). Keywords work behind the scenes to tell Google which searches your ad should show up for.

Question: How did you come up with the keyword suggestions I see here?
Answer: We generate keyword suggestions using everything you’ve already told us about your business: your answers in the Brainstorm step, your landing page content, your headlines and details, and your location or service area where relevant. We look for phrases that real customers are likely to type into Google when they want what you offer, then surface those as starting points for you to review, edit, and approve.

Question: How many keywords should I select?
Answer: On this page you’ll see a “Select 5–15” tag. We require at least 5 selected keywords so Google has enough variety to work with, and we cap the list at 15 so your budget stays focused. A good target for most campaigns is 8–12 well-chosen, relevant keywords rather than a very long list.

Question: What makes a “good” keyword?
Answer: A good keyword matches how your ideal customer would search for your service, and it clearly relates to what’s on your landing page. 
For example, for pet portraits: “dog photo session,” “cat portrait photographer,” or “pet photography near me.” 
A bad keyword is too broad (“photos,” “camera”) or not actually something you offer (“free pet portraits” if you don’t do them). Good keywords attract people who are ready to buy from you; bad keywords waste your budget on irrelevant searches.

Question: Can I add my own keywords, or am I limited to the suggestions?
Answer: You can absolutely add your own keywords. Use the main input field at the top to type and add additional terms. We’ll show them in the list alongside our suggestions so you can review, edit, and confirm them using the lock button just like any other keyword.

Question: How do I bulk add multiple keywords at once?
Answer: To bulk add, you can type or paste several keywords into the main “Enter keywords” field, separated by commas or line breaks. When you click Add, we’ll split them into individual keyword rows. From there you can edit any keyword, remove ones you don’t like, and click the lock button to choose which ones you want to include in your campaign.

Question: What does “Refresh Suggestions” do for keywords?
Answer: “Refresh Suggestions” asks our AI to propose a new set of keyword ideas based on your latest business and landing page information. Any keywords you’ve manually added or edited will remain intact. We only replace or add to the unedited suggestion slots, so you don’t lose work you’ve already customized.
Answer: “Refresh Suggestions” will:
Ask the AI to generate a new set of keywords


Leave any existing keywords you have edited and locked in place.
Add the new suggestions below keywords that are already locked 

Question: What does the lock icon next to a keyword do?
Answer: The lock icon lets you protect a specific keyword that you definitely want to keep in your campaign. When you lock a keyword, it is treated as a keyword that will be included in your campaign as long as it passes Google’s policy checks, and it will not be removed or swapped out when you click “Refresh Suggestions.

Question: Do I need to worry about keyword match types (broad, phrase, exact)?
Answer: We handle match types for you using Google’s recommended defaults so you don’t have to worry about every technical detail. Behind the scenes, we format your keywords so your ads can show on close variations and natural ways people search for the same idea, while still keeping things relevant

Question: Should my keywords be short or long phrases?
Answer: It’s useful to have a mix, but we recommend leaning toward specific, intent-rich phrases. Shorter keywords like “pet photographer” reach more people but can be too broad for smaller campaigns that are just getting started. Longer “long-tail” phrases like “pet portrait photographer in Brooklyn” often bring more qualified searchers who know what they want. A healthy set combines a few broader core terms with several more specific phrases tied to your location, service type, or niche.

Question: Can I target more than one city or service area with my keywords?
Answer: Yes. You can include location terms in your keywords (for example, “pet photographer Brooklyn,” “pet photographer Queens”). In addition, your campaign’s geographic targeting settings determine where your ads can show. Keywords tell Google what people are searching for; location settings tell Google where the searcher should be. We’ll guide you through location settings on the next step, so you don’t have to cram every possible city into your keyword list.

Question: What if I don’t know what keywords to use at all?
Answer: If you’re not sure where to start, you can rely on our suggestions. First, review the list we generated, remove anything that doesn’t match what you offer, and lock the ones that feel right. If something still feels off, click “Refresh Suggestions” and we’ll create new keyword suggestions for you. You can always come back and refine your keywords later after you see which searches are driving clicks and customers.

Question: Will changing my keywords later affect my campaign?
Answer: Yes. When you add, remove, or edit keywords after launch, your ads become eligible for a different set of searches. That can improve results if you’re tightening up relevance or expanding into a new niche. In reporting, you may see a short adjustment period while performance stabilizes around your new keyword set. It’s normal to review your keywords regularly and tune them based on what’s working.


Question: How does the Ad Preview at the top work?
Answer: At the top of the page you’ll see an Ad Preview card:
It shows a sample combination of your content, not every possible version.
Different customers in Google Search may see different headline/description combinations than the one in the preview.

The preview is meant to help you visualize the ad and check for typos, tone, and messaging—not to represent all variations.

Plan - Settings
Location Targeting
Question: What is Location Targeting and why does it matter?

Answer: Location Targeting tells Google where potential customers should be when they see your ad. 

For a local service business, this might be your city plus a radius around it

For an online-only business, it might be specific regions or countries you serve. 

Getting this right helps you avoid paying for clicks from people who live too far away or who cannot realistically become customers.

Question: How do I change my Location Targeting?

Answer: Start typing the name of a location (for example, “San Fran”) in the search bar.

The system will suggest matching locations (like “San Francisco, CA, City, US” or “San Francisco County, CA, County, US”).

Click on a suggestion to add it to your list of targeted locations and set a radius around that location if you would like. If you choose a specific address, it’s important to include a radius to capture the area around that address. 

You can toggle each location between “Targeted” and “Excluded” to fine-tune your campaign (for example, target all of California except San Francisco). 

You can remove any location from your list at any time. At least one targeted location is required to save your settings. Make sure not to duplicate locations between your targeted and excluded lists.

Question: Should I start with a broad area (like the whole country) or a narrow local radius?

Answer: If you are a local service business (for example, pet photographer, plumber, HVAC, dentist), we strongly recommend starting with a narrow local focus: your city or a radius that roughly matches your real service area. This keeps your budget concentrated on people who can actually work with you. If you sell fully online and can serve customers anywhere, targeting a broader region or country can make sense, but you may still want to start with your strongest markets first.

Question: What does the “Targeted / Excluded” toggle mean next to a location?
Answer: Each location can be set as either Targeted or Excluded.
Targeted means “show my ads to people in or interested in this area.”
Excluded means “do not show my ads to people in this area.” You might exclude a nearby city you don’t serve, or a location where you cannot ship. To change it, use the toggle on the location pill.
Question: Can I add multiple locations or different radiuses?
Answer: Yes. You can add several locations by typing them into the location search bar one by one. For some types of locations (like a city or address), you can also set a radius around that point (for example, 10 miles). This is useful if you serve certain neighborhoods but not an entire metro area. 
Just be sure your combined locations still reflect areas you’re truly willing to serve so you don’t waste budget.
Question: I work from home but serve clients in their homes or offices. How should I set Location Targeting?

Answer: In that case, you should target the areas where your clients are, not your home address specifically. 

For example, if you’re a mobile pet photographer in Brooklyn and Queens, you might target those boroughs or a radius that covers them. Avoid targeting the entire country if you don’t travel that far because your ads will reach people who are too far away to hire you.

Question: I sell online and can work with anyone in the country. How should I set Location Targeting?

Answer: If your service is truly national (for example, a digital product or online consulting), you can select your entire country as your location. If you know certain regions convert much better (for example, East Coast or specific states), you may want to start with those areas first, then expand once you see results. The key is to match your targeting to where you can deliver your product or service reliably.

Ad Schedule
Question: What is the Ad Schedule and what does it control?

Answer: The Ad Schedule determines which days of the week and hours of the day your ads are eligible to run. For example, you might choose the default of Monday–Friday from 9:00 AM to 5:00 PM to align with your business hours, or select “Always On” to let Google show your ads 24/7. This helps you align your ad spend with when customers are most likely to contact you or when you can respond quickly.

Question: How do I change the days and hours my ads run?

Answer: On this page, click the day buttons (Mon, Tues, etc.) to turn each day on or off, or use “Always On” if you want all days. Then edit the Start Time, End Time, and Time Zone using the dropdowns.

Question: Should I only run ads during my business hours?

Answer: It depends on how your customers typically contact you.

If most leads call you and you want someone available to answer, it often makes sense to run ads mainly during business hours.

If leads usually fill out a form, request callbacks, or book online, running ads longer hours or 24/7 can work well, as long as you respond promptly when you’re back online.

You can start with your business hours, then expand if you see demand outside those times.

Question: What does the Time Zone setting affect?
Answer: The Time Zone setting tells Google which local time your Start Time and End Time refer to. For example, if you choose 9:00 AM to 5:00 PM and “Eastern Standard Time,” your ads will run during that window in Eastern time. Make sure this matches where you operate or where your customers are, so you don’t accidentally show ads overnight or miss your peak hours.
Daily Budget
Question: What is the Daily Budget and how is it used?

Answer: The Daily Budget is the average amount you’re comfortable spending per day on this campaign. Google uses it to pace your ad spend across the month. On some days you might spend a little more or less than your daily setting, but over a month it aims to average out to roughly your daily budget multiplied by the number of days in the month.

Question: How much should I set as my Daily Budget?

Answer: A good starting point depends on your industry and goals, but you generally want a budget that can generate a meaningful number of clicks each week. 

We recommend that you aim to generate 10-15 clicks per day at a minimum, which can mean $50 or more, depending on the competitiveness of your industry and demand for your keywords

It’s often better to start with a realistic, sustainable amount than to go very low and receive almost no data or feedback from your Google ad.

Question: Is my Daily Budget a hard maximum or can Google spend more than that?

Answer: Google treats your Daily Budget as an average target. On a given day, Google might spend up to roughly twice your daily amount if there’s strong demand, and then spend less on quieter days so that, over the course of a month, you don’t exceed your daily budget multiplied by the number of days. If you want tighter control, choose a daily number that still feels comfortable even if a particular day spends a bit more.

Question: Can I change my Daily Budget later?

Answer: Yes. You can adjust your budget at any time by returning to your Campaign Settings within your Dashboard. Increasing your budget can help you capture more traffic if your ads are working well; decreasing it can help you manage spend if you’re testing or optimizing

Question: What happens if I pause or stop my campaign—am I still charged my Daily Budget?

Answer: If you pause a campaign, your ads stop showing and you stop accruing new charges. You won’t be billed your full Daily Budget on days when the campaign isn’t running. Any previous spending stays in your Google billing history, but no new clicks are charged while paused. You can resume later and pick up where you left off.

Question: Will my budget and settings affect how fast I get results?

Answer: Yes. A small budget or very narrow schedule/location can limit how many impressions and clicks you get, which slows down how quickly you learn what’s working. 

A larger budget, well-targeted locations, and an appropriate schedule give Google more opportunities to show your ads and collect data. If results feel slow, the first things to review are:
Is my location too broad or too narrow?
Are my ads running enough hours each day?
Is my daily budget large enough to get several clicks per day in my market?

Question: Can you update my Location, Schedule, or Daily Budget for me?

Answer: No. We’re happy to help explain how these settings work, suggest strategies, and help you decide what to choose, but we leave the final decisions on this page up to you. To update your Location Targeting, Ad Schedule, or Daily Budget, you must click into those controls and make the edits yourself, then save or continue.


Question: How does the Ad Preview at the top work?
Answer: At the top of the page you’ll see an Ad Preview card:
It shows a sample combination of your content, not every possible version.
Different customers in Google Search may see different headline/description combinations than the one in the preview.

The preview is meant to help you visualize the ad and check for typos, tone, and messaging—not to represent all variations.
Launch - Campaign Settings
Question: What is the Campaign Name used for and who sees it?

Answer: The Campaign Name is an internal label that helps you keep your ads organized. You will see it inside our dashboard and in your Google Ads account. Customers never see the Campaign Name. Choose something clear and descriptive, such as “Product/Service Name – Fall 2026 Launch” so you can recognize it later if you create more campaigns.

Question: How is the Campaign Name different from the Ad Group Name?

Answer: A Campaign is the higher level that controls budget, targeting, and dates. Inside each campaign are one or more Ad Groups, which hold your ads and keywords. Campaign Name describes the overall initiative, while Ad Group Name describes one specific cluster of ads and keywords within that campaign. Think of Campaign Name as the folder and Ad Group Name as the subfolder.

After the initial launch of your Campaign and first Ad Group, you will be able to add more Ad Groups to your Campaign if you would like to.

Question: How can I get help coming up with a new Campaign Name?

Answer: You have two options. You can type any name you like directly into the Campaign Name field. Or you can click Refresh Suggestions, which asks our AI to propose a name based on your business, landing page, and ad setup. You can also use the chat to request Campaign Name ideas. When you choose one of our suggestions, we will update the Campaign Name field for you.

Question: What does Campaign Type mean and why is it fixed to Google Search?

Answer: Campaign Type tells Google which channel your ads will run on, such as Search, Display, or YouTube. We focus this experience on Google Search because it is the simplest and most effective starting point for most businesses. 

To keep things straightforward and aligned with our templates, Campaign Type is fixed to Google Search for now and cannot be changed from this screen. If you would like to expand your campaign beyond Google Search, please contact the Launch10 team for help by emailing support@launch10.ai

Question: What is the “Maximize Clicks” bidding strategy and why is it selected for me?

Answer: “Maximize Clicks” tells Google to automatically set your bids in order to get as many clicks as possible within your daily budget. It is a smart bidding strategy that removes the need to set manual bids for each keyword. We set this as the default and only option for now because it is a strong, low-friction choice for early campaigns where the main goal is to drive traffic and learn what works.

If you would like to expand your campaign beyond this bidding strategy, please contact the Launch10 team for help by emailing support@launch10.ai

Question: Can I choose a different bidding strategy, like conversions or manual CPC?

Answer: To keep the setup simple and to reduce the chance of misconfigurations, this flow supports only Maximize Clicks. 

If you would like to expand your campaign beyond this bidding strategy, please contact the Launch10 team for help by emailing support@launch10.ai

Question: How do the Start Date and End Date work for my campaign?

Answer: The Start Date is the first day your ads are eligible to run. The End Date is the last day they are scheduled to run. We default the End Date to 30 days after the Start Date so you have a clear test window, but you can change either date by clicking into the date fields. After the End Date passes, your campaign stops serving automatically unless you extend the date.

Question: Can I start my campaign immediately?

Answer: Yes. If you want your ads to start as soon as your campaign is approved and launched, set the Start Date to today. Once you complete this step and finish launching, your ads will begin serving as Google processes the new campaign. If you prefer to launch in the future, pick a Start Date in the future instead.
Question: What happens if I do not set an End Date?

Answer: In most Google Ads setups, leaving no End Date means your campaign runs indefinitely until you pause or change it. We default to a 30 day End Date because most people are planning an initial test. If you choose to turn off or remove the End Date, plan to check performance regularly and pause the campaign when you no longer want to spend.

Question: Can I change the Start or End Date after my campaign is launched?

Answer: Yes. You can adjust your dates after launch by returning to your campaign settings or by editing the campaign directly in Google Ads. Changing the End Date is common if your test is going well and you want to extend it, or if you want to shorten it based on performance. 

Question: If I pause my campaign before the End Date, will it still run later?

Answer: If you pause your campaign, your ads stop serving regardless of the End Date. Google does not charge for new clicks while it is paused. When you resume the campaign, it will start serving again as long as the current date is still between the Start and End Dates. If the End Date is in the past, you will need to move it forward before the campaign can serve again.

Question: Do my Start and End Dates affect billing beyond my daily budget?

Answer: Start and End Dates just define when your campaign is active. Your actual spend is still controlled by your daily budget from the previous step. Google will not charge you extra simply because your campaign is scheduled for a longer period; it will pace spending based on your daily budget while the campaign is active.

Question: How do I know I am ready to click “Next Step” and launch?
Answer: Before moving on, make sure:

Your Campaign Name clearly describes this campaign.
Your Start Date is when you want ads to begin, and your End Date (if set) matches how long you want to run this test.

Once those are correct, you can proceed to the next step to final review and launch. If anything looks off later, you will still be able to edit your campaign settings after it starts running.

Question: How does the Ad Preview at the top work?
Answer: At the top of the page you’ll see an Ad Preview card:
It shows a sample combination of your content, not every possible version.
Different customers in Google Search may see different headline/description combinations than the one in the preview.

The preview is meant to help you visualize the ad and check for typos, tone, and messaging—not to represent all variations.

Launch - Review

Question: What happens after I launch my campaign?
Answer: After you launch, your ads will start showing to people searching for your targeted keywords. You’ll see traffic flow to your landing page, and Google Ads will track conversions (like sign-ups or demo requests). 

You can then measure results, pause underperforming ads, increase budget on winning keywords, and test new messaging to improve performance. 

Question: How can I edit something I see on the review page?

Answer: Each section has a pencil icon or “Edit Section” control. Clicking it will take you directly to the relevant editor and focus the field you want to change. After editing, your changes will be saved and reflected back on the review page.', 'live', 'faq', 'google_docs', '1t7pDbFvx2-Pq7TDJzq3hbKtaN1Q75_8rFAFJ5yIBass', 'https://docs.google.com/document/d/1t7pDbFvx2-Pq7TDJzq3hbKtaN1Q75_8rFAFJ5yIBass/edit?usp=drivesdk', '["ads", "campaigns", "google", "launch"]', '{"google_created_time": "2025-11-29T15:45:58.326+00:00", "google_modified_time": "2026-01-31T18:03:04.680+00:00"}', '2026-01-31 18:09:55.621099', '2025-11-29 17:39:07.949617', '2026-01-31 18:09:55.63213');
